üîπ Interface (Core Java)
1Ô∏è‚É£ What is an Interface?

An interface in Java is a blueprint of a class that contains abstract methods (methods without body).
It is used to achieve 100% abstraction and to define what a class must do, not how it does it.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Why Interface is Used in This Project?

In the Online Banking System, an interface is used to:

Define common banking operations

Support multiple account types

Achieve loose coupling

Enable polymorphism

3Ô∏è‚É£ Interface Used in Project
üìå IAccount Interface
interface IAccount {
    void deposit(double amt);
    void withdraw(double amt) throws Exception;
    double getBalance();
    int getAccountId();
    String getName();
}

4Ô∏è‚É£ Explanation of Methods
Method	Purpose
deposit()	Adds amount to account
withdraw()	Removes amount from account
getBalance()	Returns current balance
getAccountId()	Returns account ID
getName()	Returns account holder name
5Ô∏è‚É£ Implementation of Interface
üìå Abstract Class Implementing Interface
abstract class Account implements IAccount {
    protected int id;
    protected String name;
    protected String password;
    protected double balance;
}


‚úî Interface methods are implemented in:

Account (partially)

SavingsAccount (fully)

6Ô∏è‚É£ Polymorphism Using Interface
IAccount acc = new SavingsAccount(101, "Ashu", "1234", 5000);


‚úî Allows:

Same reference for different account types

Easy future extension (CurrentAccount, LoanAccount)

7Ô∏è‚É£ Interface in DAO & Collections
Map<Integer, IAccount> cache = new HashMap<>();


‚úî Ensures:

Generic handling of accounts

Flexibility

Clean design

8Ô∏è‚É£ Advantages of Using Interface

‚úî Achieves abstraction
‚úî Supports multiple inheritance
‚úî Improves security
‚úî Increases flexibility
‚úî Makes code scalable

9Ô∏è‚É£ Difference: Interface vs Abstract Class
Interface	Abstract Class
100% abstraction	Partial abstraction
No constructor	Can have constructor
Methods abstract	Abstract + concrete
Multiple inheritance	Single inheritance
